<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910201-0032</DOCNO><DOCID>910201-0032.</DOCID><HL>   General Dynamics   Holders Sue Company   Over Defense Awards</HL><DATE>02/01/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   GD</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><LP>   SAN DIEGO -- Three shareholders of General Dynamics Corp.filed suit against the company, its directors and topofficers for allegedly using illegal means to procure defensecontracts and allowing other fraud within the company over aperiod of several years.   Herman Krangel, Lilian Krangel and Rhoda Kanter, in acomplaint filed in state court here on Jan. 17, charged thedefendants with a litany of wrongdoing, claiming that theirconduct resulted in reduced profit and government lawsuitsagainst the St. Louis company.</LP><TEXT>   In one example, the suit claims that management allowedcost overruns and delays on the A-12 Advanced TacticalAircraft contract, leading to the project's recentcancellation by Defense Secretary Dick Cheney.   Many of the allegations in the suit stem from federalactions in &quot;Operation Ill Wind,&quot; the long-runninginvestigation of defense procurement fraud, and awhistleblower suit won last year by a former General Dynamicsfinancial analyst.   The current suit seeks unspecified damages. A spokesmanfor General Dynamics said that the company has &quot;noconfirmation that such a suit has been filed.&quot; He wouldn'tcomment on the allegations.</TEXT></DOC>